# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albert-broadbent-vegetarian
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The **United Kingdom Census 1901** was the 11th nationwide census conducted in the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, and was done on 31 March 1901 "relating to the persons returned as living at midnight on Sunday, March 31st".
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The total population of the England and Wales, Scotland, and Ireland (including what is now the Republic of Ireland) was 41,458,721 of which 21,356,313 were female and 20,102,406 were male.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] It was divided into three parts: England and Wales, Scotland, and Ireland.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The census in England, Wales and Scotland was legislated for by the Census (Great Britain) Act 1900.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The England and Wales part of the census contains records for 32 million people and 6 million houses.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] Certain parts of the records have suffered damage and therefore some information is missing, but it is largely complete with the exception of parts of Deal in Kent.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The census of England and Wales does not include the census of Scotland.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The Isle of Man is included in the England and Wales returns.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The data for the census of Scotland is held by the National Records of Scotland, whereas the census for England and Wales is held by the National Archives.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] Prior to the secession of the Irish Free State, the whole of Ireland engaged in the census on the same night, however none of the census returns from Ireland for the 19th century still exist, except for partial returns.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The 1901 census is the first complete surviving census, and is available online.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The census in Ireland was legislated for by the Census (Ireland) Act 1900.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The term "idiot" on the 1891 census was replaced by the term "feeble-minded".
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The census data for England and Wales was first published online on 2 January 2002 on a site run by The National Archive.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] However, by early afternoon that first day, the site had crashed due to huge demand and remained offline for 11 months "Prisoners nailed for loose screws in online census".
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] This went on to spark huge interest in family history and many television series were made based on this and related information.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] Since then the data has also been available on other sites on a subscription basis.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] The data is mainly used by genealogists, family historians, name researchers and anyone wanting to know more about their Welsh and English ancestors in 1901.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/1901-united-kingdom-census] It can also be used to research hamlets, villages and parishes to build a historical perspective.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-breeze-harper] Harper attributes her initial interest in practicing veganism to the influence of the work of Dick Gregory in connecting diet to the liberation struggle of marginalized groups, and to Afrocentric, raw foodist Queen Afua.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-breeze-harper] In 2015, Harper organized a conference, *The Vegan Praxis of Black Lives Matters*, to discuss intersectional issues concerning veganism and the Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-breeze-harper] In the same year, Harper joined the advisory board for *Black Vegans Rock*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-breeze-harper] Harper was the Humane Party's vice-presidential nominee for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] The firm was founded in 1807 by Charles and Adam Black in Edinburgh.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] In 1851, the company purchased the copyrights to Sir Walter Scott's *Waverly* novels for £27,000.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] The company moved to the Soho district of London in 1889.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] During the years 1827–1903 the firm published the seventh, eighth and ninth editions of the *Encyclopædia Britannica*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] This was purchased from Archibald Constable after his company's failure to publish the seventh edition of the encyclopedia.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] Adam Black retired in 1870 due to his disapproval of his sons' extravagant plans for its ninth edition.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] This edition, however, would sell half a million sets and was released in 24 volumes from 1875 to 1889.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] Beginning in 1839, the firm published a series of travel guides known as *Black's Guides*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] The company was the publisher of the annual *Who's Who* (since 1849) and also, since 2002, the *Whitaker's Almanack*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] Other notable works include *Black's Medical Dictionary* and the *Know The Game* series of sports rules and laws reference books.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] Black Colour Books: Twenty Shilling Series* (1901–21), a "range of high-quality colour collectable picture books" which are still collected by bibliophiles.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] Wodehouse's first book, *The Pothunters*, and went on to produce many of his early works.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] In 1989 A & C Black purchased both Christopher Helm Publishers and later the Pica Press, publishers of the Helm Identification Guides, from Christopher Helm.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] In 2000 A & C Black was purchased by Bloomsbury Publishing Plc, which continued producing the former's range of reference works.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] Poyser and their back-list of around 70 ornithology titles were acquired from Elsevier Science.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] A & C Black purchased Methuen Drama from Methuen Publishing in 2006, and acquired Arden Shakespeare from Cengage Learning in 2008.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-c-black] In 2016, A & C Black Music list moved to Collins Learning, a division of HarperCollins Publishers Ltd.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] In 1893, Cole prepared a set of vegetarian menus that received high commendation at the Universal Cookery Exhibition.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] The menus were later published as "Menus for a Week in November" in Rachel Swain's *Swain Cookery* and in Florence I.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] Nicholson's *The Jubilee Cookery Book: Vegetarian Recipes*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] Cole worked in several London vegetarian organisations.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] Tovey in founding the Battersea, Clapham and Wandsworth Vegetarian Society, with A.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] She was a committee member of the Women's Vegetarian Union and gave a cookery lesson for the union at the offices of the Vegetarian Federal Union in 1898.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] According to James Gregory, Cole worked as an assistant to Nicholson and later to Charlotte Despard.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] She succeeded Nicholson as editor of *The Children's Realm*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] By 1914, she was honorary secretary of the Vegetarian Federal Union.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] Cole gave public talks and demonstrations on vegetarian cookery.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] In 1910, as secretary of the West London Vegetarian Society, she gave a cookery demonstration at a vegetarian dinner held by the society at Pirbright Hall, Southfields.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] In 1913, as honorary secretary of the London Vegetarian Society, she spoke on "What is Vegetarianism" at a meeting at the Adult School in Sutton.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] In July 1915, *The Jewish Chronicle* published an interview with Cole, then secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, on vegetarianism and Jewish dietary practice.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] She argued that a vegetarian diet was compatible with Jewish religious observance and discussed food economy during the First World War.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] In 1917, when described as a former organising secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, she gave cookery demonstrations for the Food and Cookery Association in Southampton, where she presented vegetarian menus and methods for reducing food waste.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] Cole was listed as secretary of the Children's Dinner Fund in 1916.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] Hilda Kean writes that Nicholson established the fund for underfed children, distributing cheap meals of vegetable soup, wholemeal bread, and wholemeal currant bread.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-m-cole] In 1921, Cole was honorary secretary and organiser of the Women's Freedom League Settlement in Nine Elms, which provided daily penny and halfpenny hot meals for more than 100 children and operated a milk depot.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] He became a vegetarian as a young man through reading the work of T.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] Bailey Walker and joined the Vegetarian Society in 1877.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] He worked as an analytical chemist in Manchester and for James Woolley, Sons and Co., manufacture chemists.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] Duncan had studied with Carl Remigius Fresenius.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] He was also a Fellow of the Chemical Society.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] In 1884, Duncan authored a pamphlet *The Chemistry of Foods*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] It was republished as *The Chemistry of Food and Nutrition* by the Vegetarian Society in 1905.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] Forward noted that Duncan had given "valuable aid to the Vegetarian Society in connection with the chemistry of food, and has contributed many useful essays and papers on the subject".
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] Duncan was on the executive committee of the Vegetarian Society in 1880 and later served as a vice-president.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] In 1899, Duncan commented that "a grain of wheat contains everything that is required for nutrition and these constituents are in the right proportion, so that were it necessary we could live on wheatmeal bread and water alone".
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] He later moved to New South Wales, Australia but remained in contact with vegetarians in England and was an officer for the Vegetarian Society in 1935.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] He married Annie Margaret Allison in 1890.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] They had two children: Frank and Phyllis.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] Duncan died in Punchbowl, New South Wales in 1946, aged 90.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/a-w-duncan] He was privately cremated at Rockwood crematorium.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent later became a Bible Christian deacon and lay preacher.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He was also a Fellow of the Statistical Society and a Fellow of the Royal Horticultural Society.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He died in 1912 after a nervous breakdown, following financial losses connected with his restaurant ventures.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Albert Broadbent was born in Hollingworth on 17 February 1867 to Joseph Broadbent and Mary Ann Broadbent.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He was baptised in Tintwistle on 12 May 1867.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He became a vegetarian at the age of 26 after hearing a speech by Richard Coad.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent originally intended to pursue a commercial career, but joined the staff of the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became its secretary in 1895.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He was also editor of the society's journal, *The Vegetarian Messenger and Health Review*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent represented the society at international congresses in Paris, Dresden, St.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He was active in the Vegetarian Federal Union and attended its meetings from 1893.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent lectured on vegetarianism and dietetics.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] In 1907, he published an abridged edition of Howard Williams' *The Ethics of Diet*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent's 1902 book *Science in the Daily Meal* argued that a vegetarian diet could support physical development and included 100 recipes free of uric acid.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] The book promoted the use of plasmon, which was disputed among some vegetarians.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Sandlands replied to Broadbent's book with *Science in the Daily Meal Criticised, or Plasmon Confounded*.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent founded vegetarian restaurants in Edinburgh, Aberdeen, and Leicester.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Scott, the restaurants were intended to improve women's employment prospects by providing work at a living wage, and to make low-cost vegetarian meals available to poorer customers.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] The venture failed and caused Broadbent financial loss.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He served in Congregational, Unitarian, and Labour Churches.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent was a Fellow of the Statistical Society and a Fellow of the Royal Horticultural Society.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent edited and published the *Broadbent Treasuries of Poets*, a series of 14 books.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He also edited and published six literary miniatures.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] Broadbent married Christina, daughter of William Harrison of Manchester, in 1892.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] After what Scott described as a complete nervous breakdown, Broadbent died on 21 January 1912 at his home in Longsight, Manchester.
[src:albert-broadbent-vegetarian/albert-broadbent-vegetarian] He was buried in Southern Cemetery on 25 January.
